00:00:09.496 --> 00:00:11.755
but it's really the same
ideas that we've done

00:00:11.755 --> 00:00:14.207
when we factored things with one variable.

00:00:14.207 --> 00:00:15.942
So, for example, up here in the numerator,

00:00:15.942 --> 00:00:19.029
while I never liked having
a non-one coefficient

00:00:19.029 --> 00:00:20.730
on the second degree term here,

00:00:20.730 --> 00:00:22.485
I mean, sometimes you have to,

00:00:22.485 --> 00:00:25.899
but it looks like every term
here is divisible by five,

00:00:25.899 --> 00:00:27.521
so let's factor out of five first.

00:00:27.521 --> 00:00:29.827
So the numerator, I can rewrite

00:00:29.827 --> 00:00:33.557
as five times,

00:00:33.557 --> 00:00:37.216
five times, you factor out of
five here, you get x squared.

00:00:37.216 --> 00:00:41.416
Factor out of five
here, you get plus four.

